#. type: Title ==
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:71
#, no-wrap
msgid "Sharing Scientific Names"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:74
msgid ""
"The Darwin Core supports more than one way to share a scientific name. This "
"includes the following options:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:75
#, no-wrap
msgid "A. Concatenated in the scientificName field"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:81
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| scientificName\n"
"\n"
"| Gerardia paupercula var. borealis (Pennell) Deam\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:84
msgid ""
"The *dwc:scientificName* field stores the full scientific name of a taxon "
"including authorship. This field should always be populated with data even "
"if the names are split into component parts (as in C. below). Databases that "
"do not provide a clean separation between the name part and the authorship "
"part of the name should use this field for the entire concatenated name "
"string. This may be needed for hybrid formulas, *sensu strictu* names, "
"autonyms and other non-trivial binomials. This field is generally used in "
"combination with the *dwc:taxonRank* field to store the scientific name "
"parts of a full taxonomic list including the higher taxa."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:85
#, no-wrap
msgid "B. Separate Name and Authorship parts"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:91
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| scientificName                | scientificNameAuthorship\n"
"\n"
"| Gerardia paupercula var. borealis | (Pennell) Deam\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:94
msgid ""
"Some databases separate a scientific name into a name part and an authorship "
"part. In this case the *dwc:scientificName* and "
"*dwc:scientificNameAuthorship* fields should be used."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:95
#, no-wrap
msgid "C. Separated into name parts"
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:101
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Genus | specificEpithet | taxonRank | infraspecificEpithet | "
"scientificNameAuthorship\n"
"\n"
"| Gerardia  | paupercula          | var.          | borealis                 "
"| (Pennell) Deam\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:104
msgid ""
"The Darwin Core provides a series of terms that enable scientific names to "
"be separated into component parts. Some databases store species lists in "
"such parsed components. In this case, sharing data in this form may be an "
"option. If so, however, it is strongly recommended that an additional and "
"complete name be composed from the parts and shared in the "
"*dwc:scientificName* field (as in section A above). Note that in the table "
"above, the Darwin Core term, *dwc:subgenus*, is not displayed but represents "
"an additional name component."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:105
#, no-wrap
msgid "Infrageneric Markers"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:108
msgid ""
"If possible, please provide an infrageneric rank marker as part of the "
"scientific name to avoid confusion with the original / basionym author. For "
"example *Ageratina subgen. Apoda* R.M.King & H.Rob is preferred over "
"*Ageratina (Apoda)* R.M.King & H.Rob. as the later *Apoda* could "
"interpreted as a subgenus or as the basionym author."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:109
#, no-wrap
msgid "Publishing Classifications"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:112
msgid ""
"The Darwin Core provides two basic options for publishing classifications or "
"taxonomic hierarchies; normalized and denormalized. These two options "
"account for the primary means by which most classifications are managed in "
"databases."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:113
#, no-wrap
msgid "Normalized Classifications (Parent/Child)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:116
msgid ""
"The recommended way to share a classification is in a normalized "
"format. This may also be referred to in a database as a \"parent-child "
"relationship\" or an \"adjacency list\". In a normalized taxonomic "
"hierarchy, each taxon is represented by a single row. This includes both "
"species and all higher taxa in the classification. Each row has at least the "
"following component data elements."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:118
msgid ""
"A *dwc:taxonID* referring to the current taxon. *You can use whatever "
"identifiers you have*."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:119
msgid "The *dwc:scientificName* of the current taxon. Example: *Panthera tigris*"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:120
msgid "The *dwc:taxonRank* of the referent taxon. Example: *species*"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:121
msgid ""
"A reference to the taxon identifier of the immediate parent taxon stored in "
"the *dwc:parentNameUsageID*. In the example below, the parent of record 7, "
"for *Panthera tigris* (Linnaeus) is record 6, the genus *Panthera*."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:123
msgid ""
"A sample classification for a single species, the tiger, *Panthera "
"tigris*, is illustrated below. Note that the top-most member of a hierarchy "
"has no parent so that the parent identifier should be empty. Note that "
"*dwc:scientificName* provides a common field for storing the name in this "
"case but that the full set of options for names is described above in "
"Sharing Scientific Names."
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:134
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| taxonID | taxonRank | scientificName         | parentNameUsageID\n"
"\n"
"| 1           | Kingdom       | Animalia                   |\n"
"| 2           | Phylum        | Chordata                   | 1\n"
"| 3           | Class         | Mammalia                   | 2\n"
"| 4           | Order         | Carnivora                  | 3\n"
"| 5           | Family        | Felidae                    | 4\n"
"| 6           | Genus         | Panthera                   | 5\n"
"| 7           | Species       | Panthera tigris (Linnaeus) | 6\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:136
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:166
#, no-wrap
msgid "Advantages"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:139
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"*Efficiency*  A normalized classification stores a single reference for "
"each taxon in the hierarchy.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:140
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"*Referential integrity*  Each taxon component has a distinct identifier "
"that explicitly references its immediate parent. It is easy to verify that "
"the taxonomic hierarchy is complete and properly formed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:141
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"*Extensibility*  All taxa are identified with distinct taxon "
"identifiers. This enables higher taxa to be more richly documented through "
"the use of extensions in the same manner as species records.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:142
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:171
#, no-wrap
msgid "Disadvantages"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:145
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"*Convenience* - A normalized classification does not provide an intuitive "
"view of the classification hierarchy when viewed in raw tabular form. Many "
"biologists manage classifications in a less efficient, but more visually "
"intuitive, *denormalized format*, described below. Transforming a "
"denormalized classification to the normalized form is difficult to manually "
"perform.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:147
msgid ""
"A *dwc:parentNameUsageID* must point to an existing record in the "
"dataset. It is invalid to point to higher taxon identifiers that do not "
"exist as records."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:148
#, no-wrap
msgid "Denormalised Classifications"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:151
msgid ""
"This format is familiar to anyone who manages species information in "
"spreadsheets. In a denormalized classification, each row of the data table "
"refers to one of the terminal taxa, such as a species, and a complete set of "
"parent taxa as a set of columns, one for each parent taxon."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:153
msgid ""
"This format is not the recommended method for sharing taxonomic data using "
"Darwin Core Archives but is supported by GBIF as it is in common use in many "
"species lists. If this is the method by which data will be shared, it is "
"highly recommended that"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:155
msgid ""
"Each higher taxon column is completely populated. Avoid blanks as in the "
"Plantae example below."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:156
msgid ""
"Ensure taxonomic integrity of the list. For example ensure that two species "
"in a common genus share the same family. Ensure that if synonyms are "
"included in separate rows, that their classification matches that of the "
"accepted taxon."
msgstr ""

#. type: Table
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:164
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| taxonID | kingdom | phylum | class | order | family | scientificName\n"
"\n"
"| 1001        | Animalia    | Chordata   | Mammalia  | Carnivora   | Felidae    "
"| Panthera tigris\n"
"| 1002        | Animalia    | Chordata   | Mammalia  | Carnivora   | Felidae    "
"| Panthera leo\n"
"| 1003        | Animalia    | Arthropoda | Insecta   | Hymenoptera | Apidae     "
"| Apis mellifera\n"
"| 1004        | Plantae     | --         | --        | --          | Poales     "
"| Poa annularis\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:169
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"*Legibility* - The primary advantage of this format is that it is easy to "
"read and the taxonomic hierarchy can be evaluated by simply reading "
"columns.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:170
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"*Convenient*  Spreadsheet applications and many relational databases make "
"it easy to implement this structure for storing hierarchical data.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:174
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"*Higher likelihood of referential integrity loss*  Higher taxa are repeated "
"in this format which can increase the chance that two identical taxa may be "
"spelled differently. Other similar risks are possible with this format. For "
"example it is possible for two instances of the same taxon (example "
"Felidae) to be assigned to two different parents, resulting in a conflict "
"of hierarchical integrity.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:175
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"*Lack of details for higher taxa*  This format treats higher taxa as "
"properties of a species, not as separate taxon records "
"themselves. Therefore, this format does not allow properties of higher taxa "
"to be shared either in the core file or in any extensions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:176
#, no-wrap
msgid "Other classification-related recommendations"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:179
msgid ""
"Try to include a Kingdom and a nomenclatural code reference for all records "
"even for basic species lists."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/best-practices-checklists.adoc:180
