#. type: Title =
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/darwin-core.adoc:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Darwin Core"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/darwin-core.adoc:5
msgid ""
"Darwin Core is a http://www.tdwg.org/activities/darwincore/[TDWG] standard, "
"which is based on the ideas of the popular "
"http://dublincore.org/documents/dcmi-terms/[terms from the Dublin Core "
"Metadata Initiative].  A fundamental principle of the Darwin Core as a "
"library of terms is to keep the definition of terms distinct from the "
"technology used to share them, e.g. XML or RDF."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/darwin-core.adoc:6
#, no-wrap
msgid "IPT and Darwin Core"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/darwin-core.adoc:8
msgid ""
"The IPT has core biodiversity data types built-in, which are based on Darwin "
"Core (DwC) terms. The dataset types are Occurrence, Checklist, and Metadata "
"records, each of which has a fixed set of terms to describe it."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/darwin-core.adoc:9
#, no-wrap
msgid "Darwin Core History"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/darwin-core.adoc:13
msgid ""
"Until the ratification of Darwin Core as a standard it was used to describe "
"primary species occurrence data, in particular through DiGIR and XML "
"encoding.  When we were looking for a very simple checklist data exchange "
"format and with the rise of tagging of species on Flickr, it became apparent "
"that simple terms for biodiversity in the tradition of Dublin Core would be "
"very useful - and indeed very much overlapping with the Darwin Core terms in "
"use already."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/darwin-core.adoc:14
#, no-wrap
msgid "Terms"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/darwin-core.adoc:16
msgid ""
"All Darwin Core terms are defined in "
"http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/index.htm[Darwin Core Terms: a quick reference "
"guide]."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/darwin-core.adoc:20
msgid ""
"A single DwC term, in IPT often called a property, can be used once for each "
"record.  Generally it is free text, but the definition often recommends "
"certain formats or vocabularies to use, e.g. the ISO 2 letter country codes "
"for the `dwc:countryCode` term."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/darwin-core.adoc:21
#, no-wrap
msgid "Patterns"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/darwin-core.adoc:22
#, no-wrap
msgid "ID terms"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/darwin-core.adoc:26
msgid ""
"DwC provides many of terms for identifiers. Some can be used to define a "
"record (such as occurrenceID for an Occurrence record; taxonID for a Taxon "
"record), while others (such as higherGeographyID) refer to an identifier for "
"information stored outside the record.  For example `namePublishedInID` is "
"used to refer to an identifier (perhaps a DOI or other resolvable "
"identifier) for the publication in which a scientificName was originally "
"established.  Note that `taxonID` used within an occurrence dataset would "
"function as a pointer to a taxon defined somewhere else, such as in a "
"checklist dataset, while `taxonID` within a Taxon record would act as the "
"identifier for that record."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/darwin-core.adoc:29
msgid ""
"Most ID terms have a corresponding full text term, "
"e.g. `acceptedNameUsageID` and `acceptedNameUsage`.  These serve two "
"purposes:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/darwin-core.adoc:31
msgid ""
"In the absence of an identifier they can be used to refer to another record, "
"in this case the accepted/valid taxon."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/darwin-core.adoc:32
msgid ""
"They provide a human readable context that persists even if the identifier "
"cannot be resolved"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/darwin-core.adoc:34
msgid "It therefore makes sense to provide both if possible."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/darwin-core.adoc:35
#, no-wrap
msgid "Denormalized Hierarchies"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: en/modules/ROOT/pages/darwin-core.adoc:39
msgid ""
"The geography and taxonomy can be expressed as a flexible hierarchy of "
"places or taxa through the terms `higherParentNameUsage(ID)` and "
"`higherGeography(ID)`.  In addition to this _adjacency list_ , the most "
"popular ranks can be published as a denormalized hierarchy for each record, "
"effectively repeating this information across many records. But it does "
